    dek: `Social media is powerful, but it's not the whole of film marketing — it's one instrument in an orchestra that also includes your press kit, trailer, festival run, and word of mouth. Understanding how social fits with everything else keeps you from treating it as a magic bullet and helps it actually work.`,
    body: `<p>Before we go deep on social, I want to place it correctly, because a common mistake is treating social media as if it's the entire marketing job — or, oppositely, as a separate thing bolted onto "real" promotion. Neither is right. <strong>Social media is one part of your film's overall marketing, and it works best when it's connected to everything else you're doing.</strong> Film marketing is really the whole effort of getting your film known and wanted: your press and publicity, your festival run, your press kit and trailer, your website and email list, word of mouth, and yes, your social media. These pieces reinforce each other — a festival premiere gives you something to post about, a good trailer gives your social real content, press coverage gives you credibility to share, and your social presence in turn drives people to all of it. Understanding this ecosystem keeps you from two failure modes: expecting social alone to do everything, and running social in a vacuum disconnected from your other efforts. Let me map how the pieces fit.</p>

<h2>How the marketing pieces work together</h2>

<p>Social sits inside a larger marketing system. The main pieces and how they connect:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Your assets (EPK, trailer, stills, poster).</b> The raw material. Social has nothing to post without strong assets, and your assets reach nobody without social and press to distribute them. They feed each other.</li>
  <li><b>Press &amp; publicity.</b> Coverage in outlets and podcasts builds credibility. Social amplifies press (you share it), and a strong social following can attract press (journalists notice traction).</li>
  <li><b>Festivals &amp; screenings.</b> Prestige and events. Each festival gives you social content and a reason to post; social builds the audience that fills your screenings.</li>
  <li><b>Your website &amp; email list.</b> The home base you own. Social drives people to your site and list; unlike social followers, an email list is an audience no algorithm can take away.</li>
  <li><b>Word of mouth.</b> The most powerful force. Everything above exists to spark it — and social is where modern word of mouth largely happens, through shares and recommendations.</li>
  <li><b>Social media.</b> The connective tissue — the channel that amplifies all the others, drives people between them, and reaches your audience directly and affordably.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Making social pull its weight in the system</h2>

<p>Once you see social as connective tissue rather than a standalone magic trick, you use it much more effectively. The key principle is <strong>integration: everything you do in marketing should feed your social, and your social should point back to everything else.</strong> When you get press, you share it on social. When you premiere at a festival, you post from it. When you cut a new trailer, it becomes social content. When someone follows you on social, you guide them toward your email list — the audience you truly own. This two-way flow is what turns a scattered set of marketing efforts into a reinforcing system where each piece makes the others stronger. Two clarifications worth making. First, <em>social media is not a replacement for the rest of marketing.</em> Some filmmakers pour everything into social and neglect their press kit, their festival strategy, or their email list, and then wonder why the social effort feels like it's spinning without traction. Social works best amplifying real substance — a genuine festival run, actual press, a strong trailer — so build those too, and let social carry them further. Second, <em>your owned channels matter more than your rented ones.</em> Your social followers live on platforms you don't control, where an algorithm change can cut your reach overnight; your email list and website are yours forever. So a smart use of social is partly to convert followers into owned-audience — get people onto your email list — because that's the audience that survives platform changes and carries to your next film. As we go through the rest of this course focusing on social specifically, keep this whole-system view in the back of your mind: you're learning to play one instrument well, but it's part of an orchestra, and the music only works when they play together. Practically, that means your social strategy should always be asking "what am I amplifying, and where am I sending people," not just "what should I post." Social that's plugged into your festival run, your press, your assets, and your email list will vastly outperform social that runs in isolation. With social placed in context, we can get practical — the next chapter is about actually building your film's social presence from the ground up.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Social media isn't the whole of film marketing — it's the connective tissue. Everything you do should feed your social, and your social should point back to everything else. And convert followers you rent into an email list you own.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>I once ran a film's social account like it existed on an island — posting into the void, disconnected from anything else I was doing. Meanwhile my festival run, my press hits, and my trailer were all sitting there unused as content. When I finally integrated it — sharing every press mention, posting from every screening, funneling followers to an email list — the whole thing came alive, because the social finally had real substance to amplify and somewhere to send people. Social didn't need to do everything; it needed to connect everything. That shift did more than any single clever post.</p>
</div>`,
