    dek: `Before you post anything, you need a presence worth following — the accounts, profiles, and basic setup that make you look legit and make it easy for the right people to find you. Getting the foundation right, and deciding what the account even <em>is</em>, saves you from restarting later.`,
    body: `<p>Now we get hands-on. Before you can build an audience, you need a <strong>presence</strong> — the actual accounts and profiles that represent you and your film, set up so you look credible and so the right people can find and follow you. This sounds basic, but filmmakers routinely get it wrong in ways that cost them: a confusing account that's half personal, half film; a profile that doesn't say who you are or link anywhere; a scattershot presence on six platforms they can't maintain. The foundation you build here shapes everything after it, and one early decision in particular — <em>what is this account, and who's it for?</em> — is worth getting right before you post a single thing, because changing it later means starting over. Let me walk through building a presence that's ready to grow.</p>

<h2>Setting up a presence that works</h2>

<p>The building blocks of a credible, findable social presence:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Decide: filmmaker account or film account.</b> A personal filmmaker brand (you, across many projects) usually builds a more durable audience than a single-film account that goes quiet after release. Often the filmmaker account is the smarter long-term home, with the film featured within it.</li>
  <li><b>Pick your platforms deliberately.</b> Don't spread across everything. Choose the one or two platforms where your audience actually is and you can post consistently — better to be strong on two than weak on six.</li>
  <li><b>Nail your profile basics.</b> Clear name, a bio that says who you are and what you make, a recognizable profile image, and a link (to your site, film, or email signup). Make it obvious in three seconds who this is.</li>
  <li><b>Establish a consistent look.</b> Recognizable visual identity — consistent handles, colors, and style — so you look intentional and legit across platforms and posts.</li>
  <li><b>Set up your link destination.</b> Where your bio link sends people — ideally toward your owned home base and email signup, so followers can become an audience you keep.</li>
</ul>

<h2>The decisions that shape everything after</h2>

<p>The most consequential choice here is <strong>filmmaker account vs. single-film account,</strong> and I'll give you my honest bias: for most people, building around <em>you the filmmaker</em> beats building around one film. A single-film account has a built-in expiration — once that film's moment passes, the account has nowhere to go, the audience stops making sense, and you're starting from zero for the next project. A filmmaker account, by contrast, carries across your whole career: this film is featured now, the next one later, and the audience you build compounds instead of resetting. There are exceptions (a film with a huge distinct brand identity might warrant its own account), but as a default, invest in your durable filmmaker presence and feature the film within it. The second decision is <em>focus over spread.</em> Beginners feel they must be everywhere — TikTok, Instagram, YouTube, X, Facebook, all at once — and end up maintaining none of them well. It's far better to pick the one or two platforms where your specific audience actually spends time and where you can realistically post consistently, and go deep there. A strong presence on two platforms beats a ghost-town presence on six, every time. (We'll dig into which platform fits which film later in the course.) The third thing is to treat your <em>profile as a landing page</em>: when someone discovers a post and clicks your profile, the first three seconds decide whether they follow. So your name, bio, image, and link should instantly communicate who you are, what you make, and why they'd want more — vague or empty profiles quietly lose you followers you'd otherwise have kept. Finally, wire your presence toward your <em>owned audience</em>: your bio link and calls to action should, over time, guide interested followers to your email list or website, so you're converting rented reach into an audience you truly own (the point from the last chapter). Get these foundations right — a durable filmmaker account, focused platforms, a sharp profile, a consistent look, and a link that captures interest — and you've built a presence that's ready to actually grow, rather than one you'll have to tear down and rebuild. It doesn't need to be elaborate or expensive; it needs to be clear, consistent, and pointed in the right direction. With the presence built, the next chapter turns to the thinking behind it: your actual film marketing strategy.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Build around you the filmmaker, not just one film — a single-film account expires, but a filmmaker presence compounds across your whole career. Then go deep on two platforms instead of thin on six.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>My first film, I built a dedicated account just for it — clever name, film-specific everything. It grew a little, then the release ended and the account died, because it had nowhere to go. For the next film I started over from zero. Finally I got wise and built a filmmaker account under my own name, featured each project within it, and stopped resetting every time. That account has carried three films now, and each one starts in front of the audience the last one built. I wish I'd understood on day one: build the durable thing, not the disposable one.</p>
</div>`,
