    dek: `Posting without a strategy is just noise. A film marketing strategy is the clear thinking underneath the posts: who you're trying to reach, what you want them to feel and do, and how your film connects to them. Get the strategy right and the content decisions get easy.`,
    body: `<p>Here's where most filmmakers' social marketing quietly goes wrong: they start posting before they've decided what they're actually trying to accomplish or who they're trying to reach. The result is scattered, generic content that speaks to no one in particular and moves nothing forward. A <strong>marketing strategy</strong> is the fix — the clear thinking that sits underneath all your posts, answering who you're reaching, what you want them to feel and do, and what your film uniquely offers them. Strategy isn't a fancy corporate document; it's a handful of honest answers that make every later decision — what to post, where, in what tone — nearly automatic. When you know your strategy, you never again stare at a blank screen wondering what to post, because the strategy tells you. This chapter is about developing that thinking before Module 2 turns it into an actual plan and content.</p>

<h2>The questions your strategy answers</h2>

<p>A film marketing strategy comes down to answering these clearly:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Who exactly is your audience?</b> Not "everyone" — the specific people who'd genuinely love this film. Genre fans, a community, people who care about your subject. The narrower and truer, the more powerful your marketing.</li>
  <li><b>What's your goal?</b> Awareness, festival buzz, ticket or rental sales, building your following, driving to your email list. Different goals shape different messages and calls to action.</li>
  <li><b>What's your film's hook?</b> The one compelling thing that makes someone stop and care — the angle, the emotion, the story behind it. Your marketing leads with this.</li>
  <li><b>What do you want people to feel and do?</b> The emotion you're evoking and the action you're asking for (follow, watch the trailer, join the list, buy a ticket). Every post should serve one of these.</li>
  <li><b>What's your voice?</b> The consistent tone and personality of your marketing — earnest, funny, artful, raw. It should be authentic to you and recognizable across posts.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Why a sharp audience is the whole game</h2>

<p>If you take one thing from this chapter, make it this: <strong>the single most important, and most commonly botched, part of strategy is defining your audience narrowly and truthfully.</strong> Filmmakers desperately want their film to be "for everyone," so they market to everyone, which means they market to no one — the message is so generic it doesn't grab anybody. The counterintuitive truth is that <em>specificity is what creates connection.</em> A film marketed pointedly to the exact community, genre fandom, or interest group that would genuinely love it will pull far more real engagement than the same film marketed vaguely to a general public. When you know precisely who you're talking to, you know where they hang out, what tone reaches them, what hook they'll respond to, and what will make them care — and your content sharpens dramatically. So resist the urge to broaden; instead, get uncomfortably specific about the people most likely to love your film, and build your marketing to reach <em>them</em> powerfully rather than everyone weakly. From that audience clarity, the rest of the strategy falls into place. Your <em>goal</em> tells you what you're asking that audience to do, which shapes your calls to action. Your <em>hook</em> is the one thing about your film most likely to make that specific audience stop scrolling — lead with it relentlessly, because attention is scarce and a strong hook is what earns it. The <em>feeling and action</em> you're after keep every post purposeful: before posting anything, you can ask "what do I want someone to feel, and what do I want them to do?" and if a post serves neither, it probably shouldn't go up. And your <em>voice</em> gives your marketing a consistent, human personality that people can attach to — especially valuable for an indie, where the authentic, recognizable voice of a real filmmaker is exactly what a studio can't replicate. Notice that none of this is about tactics yet — no talk of hashtags or posting times. That's deliberate. Strategy comes first because tactics without strategy are just guessing, while tactics guided by a clear strategy are effective almost regardless of the specific tricks. A filmmaker who deeply knows their audience, goal, hook, desired feeling, and voice will market well even with basic tactics; a filmmaker with slick tactics but no strategy will spin their wheels. So do this thinking honestly and write the answers down — they become the compass for everything ahead. With your strategy clear, Module 2 gets practical, starting with turning this into a concrete marketing plan.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Marketing to "everyone" means marketing to no one. Specificity creates connection — get uncomfortably precise about the exact people who'd love your film, and reach them powerfully instead of everyone weakly.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>I made a film I was sure was "for everybody," and I marketed it that way — broad, generic, inoffensive posts aimed at the whole world. It landed with a thud. A friend making a niche genre film did the opposite: she got laser-specific about the exact fandom that would love it, spoke directly to them in their language, leaned hard on the one hook they'd care about, and built a rabid little audience who showed up. Her film "for a few thousand specific people" outperformed my film "for everyone" by a mile. Specificity wasn't a limitation. It was the whole advantage.</p>
</div>`,
