    body: `<p>You have a strategy — now you need a plan to execute it. The difference matters: strategy is <em>what</em> you're doing and <em>why</em>; the plan is <em>when</em> and <em>how</em>, laid out as an actual schedule you can follow. Without a plan, even filmmakers with a good strategy fall into posting sporadically — a burst of enthusiasm, then weeks of silence, then a panicked flurry near release. A marketing plan fixes that by mapping your content to your film's timeline in <strong>phases</strong>, so you're building and sustaining attention over months rather than spending it all at once or forgetting to post at all. The plan is what turns "I should market my film" into a set of concrete things you do on specific days. Let me show you how to build one that's realistic and effective.</p>

<h2>The phases of a film marketing plan</h2>

<p>A film's marketing life divides naturally into phases, each with a different job:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Build phase (before release).</b> Long runway of process, behind-the-scenes, and story content that grows an audience and curiosity well before the film is out. Most filmmakers start this far too late.</li>
  <li><b>Launch runway (approaching release/festival).</b> Ramping intensity — trailer drop, poster reveal, dates, key art — concentrating attention as the moment approaches.</li>
  <li><b>Release moment.</b> The peak push around premiere, festival, or availability — your biggest, most coordinated burst, asking people clearly to watch or attend.</li>
  <li><b>Sustain phase (after release).</b> Keeping the film alive with reviews, reactions, milestones, and ongoing content, so it doesn't vanish the day after launch.</li>
  <li><b>A realistic cadence.</b> A posting rhythm you can actually maintain across all phases — consistency you can sustain beats an ambitious schedule you abandon.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Making a plan you'll actually follow</h2>

<p>The most important truth about marketing plans is the same one from every "plan" chapter in these courses: <strong>a modest plan you actually execute beats an ambitious one you abandon.</strong> Filmmakers routinely design heroic content calendars — daily posts across four platforms with elaborate production — and then collapse under them within two weeks, ending up worse off than if they'd committed to something sustainable. So build your cadence around what you can <em>realistically</em> keep up given that you're also, you know, making films: maybe that's three posts a week on one platform, done consistently for months, which will vastly outperform a daily blitz you quit. Consistency compounds; sporadic bursts don't. The second key insight is to <em>start the build phase early.</em> The single most common marketing regret I hear from filmmakers is "I started too late" — they finish the film and then scramble to market it in the final weeks, having wasted the entire production period during which they could have been documenting the journey and growing an audience. The build phase is your secret weapon precisely because process content (the making-of, the challenges, the behind-the-scenes) is often more engaging than the finished promotional material, and because an audience built slowly over months is warm and invested by the time you actually release. If your film is still in production or post, you are in the build phase <em>right now</em>, and starting today is the single best marketing decision available to you. Third, map your plan to your film's <em>real timeline</em> — your festival dates, your release window, your key asset drops (trailer, poster) — so your intensity peaks when it matters and your big pushes align with actual moments rather than arbitrary dates. A trailer drop, a festival premiere, an availability date are natural spikes; plan your heaviest content around them. Fourth, think in <em>content buckets</em> so you're never staring at a blank calendar: decide on a handful of recurring content types your strategy supports (behind-the-scenes, cast/crew spotlights, the story behind the film, clips, reactions, calls to action) and rotate through them, which makes the plan both easier to fill and more varied for your audience. Finally, hold the plan loosely enough to adapt — if something resonates, do more of it; if a moment arises (a festival acceptance, a bit of press), work it in. A plan is a structure to execute against and adjust from, not a rigid script. Build a realistic, phased, early-starting plan mapped to your film's timeline with content buckets you can rotate, and you've converted your strategy into a campaign you can actually run. Next, we get into the content itself — how to create posts and clips that people actually share.</p>

<div class="pullquote">A modest plan you actually execute beats an ambitious one you abandon. Start the build phase early — the most common marketing regret is "I started too late." If your film is still in production, you're in the build phase right now.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>On an early film I did nothing during the two-year production, then tried to cram all my marketing into the six weeks before release. It was frantic and it flopped — I was introducing a film to strangers with no runway. Next film, I started posting from pre-production: the location scouts, the problems, the small victories. By release I had an audience who'd watched the whole thing come together and felt invested in it. Same films, opposite outcomes, and the only difference was that the second time I started early and kept a pace I could actually sustain. Early and steady beats late and frantic every time.</p>
</div>`,
