    kicker: "Core Craft",
    seoTitle: "Creating Content That Travels: Film Social Media Marketing | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "Film social media marketing content — how to make posts, clips, and behind-the-scenes that people actually watch and share. A working filmmaker's guide. Chapter 6 of Social Media Marketing for Films.",
    dek: `This is the heart of social marketing: making things people actually want to watch and share. The good news for filmmakers is that you have an unfair advantage — you make visual content for a living. The trick is knowing what kind of posts travel, and it's rarely the ad you'd expect.`,
    body: `<p>Content is where all the strategy and planning meets reality. You can have a perfect strategy and a beautiful plan, but if the actual posts are boring, nothing happens. So let's talk about what makes content <strong>travel</strong> — get watched, get shared, get people to care — because that's the real engine of social marketing. Here's the reframe that helps most: <em>people do not want to watch your ad.</em> The instinct is to post promotional material — "watch my film, here's the trailer, out now" — and that kind of content is the least likely to travel, because nobody shares an advertisement. What travels is content that's genuinely interesting, emotional, useful, or entertaining <em>in itself</em>, that happens to also connect to your film. As a filmmaker you're unusually well-equipped to make that, because you already create compelling visual material and you have the most interesting thing of all to share: the story of making something. This chapter is about turning that advantage into content that moves.</p>

<h2>What actually travels</h2>

<p>The kinds of content that get watched and shared for indie films:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Behind-the-scenes &amp; process.</b> How the film gets made — the craft, the problems, the small victories. Often more engaging than the film's promo, because people love seeing how things are made.</li>
  <li><b>Story &amp; the "why."</b> The personal reason you made this film, the story behind the story. Emotional and human — people connect to <em>why</em> far more than to <em>what</em>.</li>
  <li><b>Great clips &amp; moments.</b> A striking, funny, or emotional short moment that stands on its own and makes someone want more. A strong 15 seconds can do more than a full trailer.</li>
  <li><b>People &amp; personalities.</b> Cast and crew being human, relatable, funny. Audiences follow people they like — put the humans of your film forward.</li>
  <li><b>Value &amp; entertainment.</b> Content that teaches, amuses, or moves on its own terms — a filmmaking tip, a relatable moment, something genuinely worth watching whether or not you see the film.</li>
  <li><b>A clear hook in the first seconds.</b> Whatever the content, it must grab attention immediately — the first 1–3 seconds decide whether anyone watches the rest.</li>
</ul>

<h2>The principles behind content that moves</h2>

<p>Underneath those categories are a few principles worth internalizing. The first and biggest: <strong>lead with value or emotion, not with the ask.</strong> Every piece of content should be worth someone's attention on its own — interesting, moving, funny, or useful — with the connection to your film woven in rather than shouted. Content that gives before it asks earns the right to occasionally ask; content that only ever asks gets ignored. The second principle is <em>hook fast.</em> On every platform, attention is decided in the first couple of seconds, so front-load the most compelling thing — the striking image, the intriguing question, the emotional beat — instead of building up to it. A slow open loses the audience before your point lands, no matter how good the payoff. The third is <em>make it feel authentic, not polished-corporate.</em> Your advantage as an indie is realness; a rough, honest, human clip often outperforms a slick promotional one because it feels like a person, not a marketing department. Don't sand the personality off your content trying to look "professional" — the personality is the point. The fourth is <em>tell stories.</em> Humans are wired for narrative, so frame your content as little stories wherever you can — the story of a scene, of a problem you solved, of why you made the film — rather than flat announcements. "Here's the disaster that almost sank this shoot" travels; "new poster out now" doesn't. Fifth, <em>work with what you have.</em> You don't need a big production to make good content — a phone, honesty, and something genuinely interesting to show beats an expensive but boring post. Your behind-the-scenes footage, your on-set moments, your own face talking honestly about the work are all content, most of which costs nothing. And finally, <em>repurpose relentlessly.</em> One shoot day yields dozens of potential posts; one good clip can be cut for multiple platforms; one story can be told in text, video, and images. Get maximum content from minimum material, because consistency (from the plan) demands a steady supply and you make that sustainable by repurposing. Put these together — lead with value, hook fast, stay authentic, tell stories, use what you have, and repurpose — and you'll produce content that actually travels rather than promotional posts that sink. The filmmakers who win at social aren't the ones with the biggest films; they're the ones who make the most genuinely watchable content about them. Next, we look at how the individual platforms differ and where to put your energy.</p>

<div class="pullquote">People don't want to watch your ad. What travels is content that's interesting, emotional, or entertaining on its own and happens to connect to your film. Lead with value, hook fast, stay real, and tell stories.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>My best-performing post ever wasn't the trailer or the poster — it was a shaky phone video of a light rig collapsing on set and the whole crew cracking up, with a caption about how nothing ever goes to plan. It cost nothing, took thirty seconds to shoot, and it traveled further than any polished promo I ever made, because it was human and funny and real. Meanwhile my slick "out now" posts sank. That taught me the whole lesson: people don't share ads, they share moments. Give them a moment worth sharing, and let the film ride along with it.</p>
</div>`,
