    seoTitle: "Platform by Platform: Marketing in Film Across Social Platforms | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "Marketing in film across social platforms — how Instagram, TikTok, YouTube, and the rest differ, and where to focus your film marketing effort. A working filmmaker's guide. Chapter 7 of Social Media Marketing for Films.",
    dek: `Marketing in film means meeting your audience where they are — and each platform is a different room with a different crowd, a different vibe, and different content rules. You don't need to master all of them; you need to know enough to choose the right one or two and use them well.`,
    body: `<p>Every social platform is its own world — a different audience, a different culture, a different kind of content that works there. Marketing in film effectively means understanding those differences enough to choose the right platforms for your film and adapt your content to each, rather than blasting the same post everywhere or trying to be present on all of them at once. I want to give you a working sense of the main platforms without pretending any specific tactic will stay current — platforms change constantly, so I'll focus on their <em>enduring character</em> and how to think about them, which outlasts any particular trick. The goal isn't to master every platform; it's to pick your one or two deliberately and use them well, which beats a thin presence spread across all of them. Let me walk the landscape.</p>

<h2>The character of the main platforms</h2>

<p>Broad strokes — the durable nature of each, which matters more than any current feature:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Short-form video (TikTok, Reels, Shorts).</b> The biggest discovery engine for indies — content can reach far beyond your followers. Rewards authentic, hook-fast, entertaining short video. Often the single best lever for a small film (its own chapter next).</li>
  <li><b>Instagram.</b> Visual-first, good for a polished-but-personal presence — stills, clips, stories, behind-the-scenes. Strong for building a filmmaker brand and community, more follower-based reach.</li>
  <li><b>YouTube.</b> Home of longer video, the trailer, and process content that lives forever in search. Less about the feed, more a durable library people find over time.</li>
  <li><b>X / Facebook / others.</b> Community, conversation, niche groups, and event promotion. Value depends heavily on where your specific audience actually gathers.</li>
  <li><b>Where your audience actually is.</b> The real deciding factor — the "best" platform is wherever the specific people who'd love your film spend their time, which flows from your strategy's audience.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Choosing and using platforms wisely</h2>

<p>The most important principle is the one that keeps recurring: <strong>go where your audience is, and go deep on one or two rather than thin on six.</strong> A film aimed at a young, trend-driven audience lives or dies on short-form video; a film for an older or more niche crowd might do better on Facebook groups or YouTube; a visually striking film might shine on Instagram. There's no universally correct platform — there's the one where <em>your</em> audience gathers, which you identified back in your strategy. Pick based on that, plus honest self-assessment of which platform you can actually create good content for consistently, and commit to it. Trying to maintain a strong presence everywhere is the fastest route to maintaining a weak presence everywhere. The second principle is <em>adapt content to each platform, don't just cross-post identically.</em> A vertical, fast-cut, hook-in-one-second video that flies on TikTok will feel wrong as a static Instagram grid post or a long YouTube upload — the same underlying material should be recut and reframed for each platform's native style. Cross-posting the exact same thing everywhere signals "I don't understand this platform" and underperforms. That said, you can absolutely <em>repurpose</em> one piece of material into platform-appropriate versions (the repurposing principle from the last chapter) — the point is to reshape, not to blindly duplicate. Third, if I had to name the single highest-leverage platform for most indie filmmakers today, it's <em>short-form video</em>, because of one structural advantage: its discovery engine can show your content to people who don't follow you, based purely on whether the content is good. On most platforms, your reach is roughly capped by your follower count; on short-form video, a genuinely great clip can reach far beyond your existing audience, which is exactly what a small film with no audience yet desperately needs. That's why the next chapter... well, actually the whole next chapter is devoted to short-form video, because for indies it's that important. Fourth, don't neglect <em>YouTube as a permanent home</em> for your trailer and longer content — unlike feed posts that vanish in a day, YouTube content stays findable in search for years, quietly working long after you post it, which makes it valuable even if it's not where the daily action is. Finally, remember that platforms are <em>tools, not the goal</em> — the goal is reaching and moving your audience, and the platform is just the room you do it in. Pick your rooms based on where your people are, use each in its native language, lean into short-form video's discovery power, keep a durable home on YouTube, and don't spread yourself so thin that you do all of it badly. Next, let's go deep on the platform type that matters most for indies: short-form video. But first, a chapter on tying your content and platforms together into an actual campaign.</p>

<div class="pullquote">The best platform is wherever your audience actually is — and depth on one or two beats thin presence on six. Adapt content to each platform's native language, and remember: short-form video is the one place a great clip can reach far beyond your followers.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>I used to run five platforms at once, posting the identical thing to all of them, and doing a mediocre job everywhere. Burnout followed, and none of it worked. I finally admitted my audience mostly lived in two places, killed the other three accounts, and put all my energy into doing those two well — recutting content to fit each rather than copy-pasting. Engagement went up while my workload went down, because I stopped spreading myself thin and started speaking each platform's actual language. Fewer rooms, done properly, beat every room done halfway.</p>
</div>`,
