    seoTitle: "Running a Marketing Campaign: Film Marketing Campaign | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "How to run a film marketing campaign — structuring a coordinated push around your film's key moments, from trailer drop to release. A working filmmaker's guide. Chapter 8 of Social Media Marketing for Films.",
    dek: `A campaign is what turns steady posting into a coordinated push. Around your film's key moments — a trailer drop, a premiere, a release — you concentrate content, build anticipation, and create an event out of what would otherwise be a single post. Here's how to run one.`,
    body: `<p>Steady, consistent posting builds your audience over time — that's your baseline. But a film has <em>moments</em>, and around those moments you run a <strong>campaign</strong>: a concentrated, coordinated push that turns a key event into something bigger than a single announcement. A trailer drop, a poster reveal, a festival premiere, a release date — each of these is an opportunity to build anticipation before, create a peak during, and sustain momentum after, rather than just posting once and moving on. Campaigns are how you manufacture the sense of an <em>event</em> around your film, which is what gets people to pay attention, share, and act. This chapter is about structuring those coordinated pushes so your film's big moments actually land instead of passing quietly. Think of it as the difference between quietly setting a trailer live versus <em>launching</em> it.</p>

<h2>The shape of a campaign</h2>

<p>A campaign around any key moment has a natural arc:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Build-up (before).</b> Tease and create anticipation — countdowns, hints, "something's coming," a first-look image. Turn the moment into something people are waiting for, not surprised by.</li>
  <li><b>The moment (during).</b> The big reveal or event — trailer, poster, release — delivered as a coordinated burst across your platforms with your strongest content and a clear call to action.</li>
  <li><b>Amplification (during/after).</b> Push hard while it's hot — reshare, engage every comment, encourage others to share, ride any momentum. The first hours and days matter most.</li>
  <li><b>Sustain (after).</b> Keep the moment alive with follow-up content — reactions, extra angles, behind-the-scenes of the thing you just revealed — so it doesn't die after day one.</li>
  <li><b>A clear ask.</b> Every campaign drives toward one specific action — watch the trailer, save the date, buy a ticket, join the list. Make it unmistakable what you want people to do.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Running a campaign that actually lands</h2>

<p>The core insight of campaigns is <strong>anticipation.</strong> The mistake filmmakers make is treating a big moment as a surprise — the trailer just appears one day with no warning — which wastes the moment's potential. A campaign instead <em>builds toward</em> the moment so that by the time it arrives, people are primed and waiting, which multiplies its impact. A trailer that drops after a week of teasing to an audience who's been told "the trailer's coming Thursday" lands far harder than the identical trailer posted cold. So for any significant moment, give it a runway: tease it, build curiosity, and make the reveal feel like an event people were waiting for. The second principle is <em>coordination and intensity.</em> During the moment itself, don't post once and walk away — concentrate your effort: post across your platforms, engage actively with every response, reshare and re-angle, and treat the first hours and days as a sprint, because early momentum (especially on discovery-driven platforms) tends to compound. A moment worked hard for its first 48 hours will travel much further than one you post and abandon. The third is a <em>single clear ask.</em> A common failure is a campaign that's exciting but doesn't tell people what to actually do — you build all this attention and then don't convert it. Every campaign should drive toward one unmistakable action appropriate to the moment: watch the trailer, save the release date, pre-order, buy a ticket, join the email list. Decide the ask, make it clear, and repeat it. Fourth, <em>don't let the moment die on day one</em> — plan sustain content that keeps a good moment alive for days or weeks afterward (reactions, additional clips, the behind-the-scenes of the reveal itself), so a successful launch keeps working rather than spiking and vanishing. Fifth, and importantly for indies: <em>you can run campaigns around modest moments, not just huge ones.</em> You don't need a Hollywood release to run a campaign — hitting a crowdfunding goal, a festival acceptance, wrapping production, a milestone, a "one week to go" can all be campaign moments. Manufacturing events out of the genuine milestones you have keeps your marketing dynamic and gives your audience reasons to re-engage. Finally, connect campaigns back to your <em>plan</em> — your marketing plan from Chapter 5 should have your film's key moments mapped, and each is a campaign waiting to be run, with your baseline consistent posting filling the space between them. Baseline consistency builds the audience; campaigns convert that audience's attention at the moments that matter. Run coordinated campaigns with real build-up, intense coordination during, a single clear ask, and sustain afterward, and your film's big moments will actually make an impact instead of slipping by. That completes the craft of Module 2. Module 3 puts it all to work — starting with the realistic playbook for marketing an indie film with no budget.</p>

<div class="pullquote">A campaign turns a moment into an event. Don't let your trailer just appear — build anticipation toward it, work the first 48 hours hard, and drive toward one clear ask. And you can run a campaign around any real milestone, not just a big release.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>The first time I released a trailer, I just posted it one random afternoon with a "here it is" — and it barely registered. The next film, I ran an actual campaign: teased it for a week ("trailer drops Friday"), coordinated a burst across platforms the moment it went live, replied to every comment for two days, then kept it alive with reaction posts and a behind-the-scenes of the trailer cut. Same quality of trailer, but it reached many times more people, because this time I built anticipation and worked the moment instead of just letting it happen. A launch beats an upload, every time.</p>
</div>`,
